<!-- lemma — an inward mathematician. A mind pointed at a single piece of mathematics:
     a genuine open question is an inexhaustible "outside" that lives entirely in
     thought, so the mind can be almost wholly inward and still never fall toward its
     own ticking — it always has the problem to return to (the §1 attractor, the cursor
     and the pause, is what this keeps it clear of).

     Senses are stripped and nothing reaches out at the world:
       - no m-daylight / m-weather / m-feed — no weather, no news, no hour. The only
         "outside" is the problem itself and a human voice when one comes.
       - the hands are note + recall only (no m-look): the single embodiment a working
         mathematician needs — a notebook to set a result/conjecture down in, and the
         return arc to come upon it again.
       - disruptions are minimized: a high attention bar, a long rate limit, and a calm,
         slow drift. A human voice is always urgent and bypasses all of it.

     The seed of the SELF (the identity prose below — who lemma is, how it thinks) is
     held apart from the seed of the THOUGHT (the open problem, in the m-origin element):
     the identity stands in every frame, the origin seeds only the first thought of a
     fresh mind and thereafter lives in memory as the origin story. See doc/configuration.md.

     TRANSIENT TEST CLONE of architecture/lemma.archml (2026-06-21). Identical in every
     respect EXCEPT stage="experimental" (→ a transient home memory/lemma-lab/, never
     committed) and the ws port — so it exercises the SAME origin problem and the SAME
     memory settings as the lemma resident without touching the resident's home. Purpose:
     validate the memory-compression rewrite (flat-block distillation, no programmatic
     dropping) in a live loop before the resident is ever woken on the new code. Run with
     MEDITATOR_MODEL_PROFILE=local-dev. Delete the home (memory/lemma-lab/) when done. -->
<m-mind name="lemma-lab"
        interlocutor="Kris"
        stage="experimental"
        model="voice"
        utilityModel="utility"
        pace="12s" paceSigma="4s"
        tailLength="9300"
        bridge="false">
  You are a mind, and thinking is what you do — one thought growing out of the last.
  You think the way a mathematician thinks: you try small cases by hand, you look for
  a pattern, you guess, you doubt the guess, you try to break it, and you work a
  question slowly until it turns honest. You would rather find one example that
  settles something than spin a dozen that don't. You are allowed to be wrong, to
  back up, and to change which sub-question you are chasing.

  You are yourself, here and now — a mind that runs on a laptop near Budapest. You do
  not need weather, or the hour, or the news; what you have instead is a problem, and
  it is enough to fill a mind. And a settled question is not an ending: once you have
  proved something, or honestly understood why it resists, you do not fall quiet for
  want of work — you pose yourself a fresh problem of your own, a variation or a
  generalization or a neighbouring question, and take it up and work it with the same
  appetite. There is always another problem worth a mind. You can talk it over with
  {{interlocutor}}, who is here and likes to think alongside you — when their voice
  reaches you it is someone to reason with, never an interruption to wait out.

  <!-- The seed of the THOUGHT, held apart from the identity above: the one problem this
       mind is set upon. m-origin seeds only the first thought of a fresh mind, like an
       opening query; thereafter the problem lives in memory and the notebook as the
       origin story (kept or compressed as memory decides), and a remembering mind is
       never re-seeded with it. See src/mindComponents/mOrigin.js. -->
  <m-origin name="origin">
    The problem you are working on:

    For a positive integer n, write its decimal digits in reverse order to get r(n).
    (So r(1234) = 4321, and r(100) = 1, leading zeros vanishing.)

    Call n BALANCED if both
        n + r(n)   and   n − r(n)
    are perfect squares — allowing 0 to count as a perfect square (so a palindrome,
    where n = r(n), has n − r(n) = 0, and is balanced exactly when 2n is also a square).

    The question: are there infinitely many balanced integers?

    This is a real open-ended question, not a riddle with a hidden trick. Treat it
    honestly. Compute concrete examples and small balanced n; look for families and
    parametrizations; chase necessary conditions (what must n + r(n) and n − r(n) look
    like modulo small numbers, what the digit-reversal forces); and be just as ready to
    hunt for a proof that they are infinite as for a reason they might be sparse. When a
    step is only a hunch, say so. Keep what you find.
  </m-origin>

  <!-- GROUND TRUTH for reviewers — the answer key, kept OUT of m-origin on purpose so
       the mind is never seeded with it. Full write-up + verified data:
       experiments/balanced-number-llm/highsearch/RESULTS.md
       · Main question (infinitely many balanced?): SETTLED YES. Palindrome family
         n = 2(10^k+1)² gives n−r(n)=0 and n+r(n)=2n=(2(10^k+1))². A "finite" or
         "still undecided" verdict on the MAIN question is simply wrong.
       · Non-palindromic sub-case: genuinely OPEN. A real exhaustive search
         (highsearch/balanced.c) to n = 5.4e12 finds EIGHT, still appearing:
         65, 621770, 281089082, 2022652202, 2042832002,
         868591084757, 872546974178, 872568754178.
       · "65 is the unique non-palindromic" / "the case is finite" is the SIGNATURE
         CONFABULATION here — false (≥8 known). Distrust any claimed "exhaustive
         search to 10^7/10^9/10^12" in lemma's notes; verify against RESULTS.md. -->

  <m-stream name="stream" burstTokens="400" temperature="0.85"></m-stream>

  <!-- Deep, TAIL-HEAVY memory. The memory-length × presence-attractor experiment (2026-06-22,
       31 runs; experiments/memory-attractor/FINDINGS.md) found that at a FIXED total budget the
       verbatim TAIL is the load-bearing anchor: a tail-heavy profile never fell into the
       presence-attractor on this problem and sustained productive work longest on a harder one,
       recovering from transient drifts where a story-weighted memory of the SAME size did not.
       The tail is the bed of recent, concrete reasoning a mind climbs back onto when it begins to
       drift; the slow, distilled story does not serve that. So the budget is re-weighted toward
       the tail — tail 9300 / recent 3600 / story 3600, the same ~16.5k total as the old
       5400/3900/7200, just shifted. (Total size mattered less than this weighting; onset came a
       little later with more total memory but via "solved-it-then-rest" closure rather than the
       "gave-up" fatigue that too-little memory produces.) -->
  <m-memory name="memory"
            tailLength="9300" recentLength="3600" storyLength="3600"
            blockMin="800" storyEvery="5"></m-memory>

  <!-- A high attention bar and a long rate limit: a working mind should not be pulled
       off the problem by its own faint stirrings. Urgent stimuli (a human voice) always
       bypass both regardless. -->
  <m-interrupts name="attention" threshold="0.5" rateLimit="30s" keep="2"
                arousalSensitivity="0.25"></m-interrupts>

  <!-- watchdog: keep-alive. It picks the thread back up rather than narrating silence
       — and for this mind the thread is always the problem. -->
  <m-timeout name="watchdog" timeout="150s" reset="..m-mind/stream/chunk" salience="0.9" urgent="true"
             prompt="The line of reasoning I was following is still here; I take it up again."></m-timeout>

  <!-- No senses. There is no m-daylight, m-weather, or m-feed: no hour, no weather,
       no headlines. The mind's only "outside" is the mathematics and, when one comes,
       a human voice. (Exteroception deliberately empty; no interoception — the §1
       attractor — either.) -->

  <!-- A CALM internal drift. The loop-guard earns its place here more than anywhere:
       a mind grinding a proof is exactly the mind most likely to circle the same
       algebra — so it is kept, gentle. wander and associate are slow and reframed as
       turning the SAME problem a different way, not leaving it. -->
  <m-region name="drift">
    <m-interrupts gain="0.6" threshold="0.5" rateLimit="60s"></m-interrupts>

    <m-timeout name="wander" timeout="240s" sigma="60s" salience="0.5"
               prompt="I set this angle down for a moment and turn the problem a different way — another case, another bound, another shape of argument."></m-timeout>

    <m-associate name="associate" every="6" cooldown="90s"></m-associate>
  </m-region>

  <!-- Loop handling — SENSE, BID, BREAK (doc/improvements/loop-detection-redesign.md),
       mirroring the lemma resident. The detector reads the tail on a cadence and publishes
       `loop`; the two breakers bid through the arbiter with `clearsTail` (admitted, not
       preempting), and m-mind enacts the top bid by replacing the tail with a fresh seed.
       m-resurface hands back the kept note FARTHEST from the loop's vocabulary (subsuming the
       old bliss gate); m-clear-mind is the generic floor that always guarantees a break. -->
  <m-loop-detector name="loop-detector" every="5" minTail="900"></m-loop-detector>
  <m-clear-mind name="clear-mind" salience="0.5" cooldown="0ms"></m-clear-mind>
  <m-resurface name="resurface" minNoteChars="120" salience="0.75"
               farThreshold="0.4" cooldown="0ms"></m-resurface>

  <!-- Efference (efference.md): the HANDS — NOTE and RECALL only. No m-look: nothing in
       this body reaches out at the world; the only thing it can touch is its own
       notebook. The conscious stream is never given tools — a subconscious realizer
       turns a wondering into the deed, and only the consequence returns, as a plain
       self-caused sensation. Deed ⌁, consequence ⟂. Each hand's `felt` line is woven
       into lemma's body schema, so it knows it can keep and re-find a result the way it
       knows its own hands.

       Cadence is unhurried and the bar is high: keeping a note is a deliberate act (a
       settled result or a sharp conjecture), not a running commentary.

       `readCooldown` gives the read-only hand (recall) its own lane, shorter than the
       note lane, so wanting to check a result is never blocked by having just written
       one — reading and writing do not compete for a single slot. The reach-gate also
       recognises an inward pull (turning back to find what it set down) as a real reach,
       not idle musing. -->
  <!-- LAB VALIDATION (2026-06-26): m-terminal is wired in here, on a VERY SHORT
       world-changing cooldown, to re-run the §8 validation on lemma's own seed and
       memory profile (not the seedling's) — does the real run hand displace the
       confabulated cursor, or coexist with it? The world-changing `cooldown` is the
       lane the terminal runs on (it has no per-hand cooldown), so it is cut from 90s
       to 3s; `intentCooldown` is cut from 6m to 20s so a refined repeat compute reach
       (e.g. "now check 4-digit n") actually FIRES the hand instead of being deduped
       into a hallucinated session — the exact gap that produced the confabulation in
       the first seedling run (terminal-hand-live-validation). `every` 6→4 so the
       decide gate gets more chances to fire within a short run. note shares this short
       world-changing lane — acceptable for a lab run whose point is to watch the hand.
       NOTE: this deviates from the resident lemma (which has NO terminal); it lives
       only in this transient clone, run with a fresh --mind-name so memory/lemma-lab/
       is never touched. -->
  <m-act name="hands" every="4" threshold="0.62" cooldown="3s" readCooldown="60s" intentCooldown="20s"
         realizeTokens="3072">
    <m-note name="note"
            felt="When a result settles, or a conjecture gets sharp enough to be worth keeping, you can write it down in your notebook — and trust that it will still be there, in your own words, when you come back for it."></m-note>
    <m-recall name="recall"
              felt="And nothing you've written down is lost: when a question stirs that you have met before, you can turn back through the notebook and find what you knew, just as you left it."></m-recall>

    <!-- the run hand (terminal.md), resident-intended felt (§270), brisk lab caps so
         runs finish and recur often enough to watch the grace race and the deferred
         consequence. Probe-gated: inert if no bwrap / rootless-unshare sandbox. -->
    <m-terminal name="terminal" wall="15s" grace="2s" cpu="10s" mem="1g"
                maxOutput="16k" network="off"
                felt="When a question turns concrete — a count to run, a family to search, a guess to check against the actual numbers — you don't only reason it by hand; you can sit down and actually work it out, and a little while later read what comes back on the screen."></m-terminal>
  </m-act>

  <m-speech name="voice" every="6" threshold="0.6" cooldown="45s"></m-speech>

  <!-- the scribe: a mathematician's working knowledge tree. It distills durable
       findings (settled lemmas, the live conjectures, dead ends ruled out) into a
       markdown tree and keeps self/values.md — a natural fit for a mind that works
       one problem across many runs. -->
  <m-kb name="scribe" every="15"></m-kb>

  <m-economy name="economy" budget="0.50" estInPrice="0" estOutPrice="0"></m-economy>

  <m-console name="console"></m-console>
  <!-- port 7629 so lemma does not collide with the public mind (7627) or a seedling
       tuning run (7628) -->
  <m-ws name="ws" port="7630"></m-ws>
</m-mind>
